I2C - working---
i2c has 2 lines data and clock , when clock is one i2c listens to data 
on data pin , when clock is zero this is when data changes since data
line can not change when clock is 1 

---start i2c---
to start i2c we have to let ic2 know when is 8051 ready to send data 
usually i2c is in idle state (SDA = 1, SCL = 1)
to start we need to pull the data line to 0 from (SDA = 1, SCL = 1)
now ic2 can receive data from 8051 , but the data line can only change
while SCL when clock is low , and when clock is high i2c receives data
so to make sure that the next data is ready to send from 8052 we switch
SCL to 0 

---i2c start---
	initial (SDA = 1, SCL = 1)
	SDA = 0 ; i2c starts
	SCL = 0 ; to get next data bit ready to send 

---stop i2c---
to stop i2c we need to create a low to high transition on SDA while SCL is high
If SDA goes High before SCL goes High, the receiver might not see it as a 
"Stop" signal; it might just see it as a normal data bit.

---i2c stop---
	make sure SDA = 0
	make SCL = 1
	make SDA = 1
